                    .option("header", true)
                    .options(Map(
                                  "header" -> "true",
                                  "dateFormat" -> "MM/dd/yyyy"
                            ))
                    .schema(schema)
                    .load("file:///media/pal/USB STICK/Spark_Usecase/nyc-parking-tickets/*.csv"))
                    .filter($"Issue Date".between("2015-01-01", "2017-12-31"))

Find the violation code frequency across three precincts which have issued the most number of tickets - do these precinct zones have an exceptionally high frequency of certain violation codes? Are these codes common across precincts?  Hint: You can analyse the three precincts together using the 'union all' attribute in SQL view. In the SQL view, use the 'where' attribute to filter among three precincts and combine them using 'union all'.
paragraphs.text:
%sql

                  (SELECT `Issuer Precinct`, `Violation Code`, count(*) as tickets_count
                   FROM Parking_Violations where `Issuer Precinct` = '19'

                   order by tickets_count desc limit 5)
        union all

                   FROM Parking_Violations where `Issuer Precinct` = '18'

                   FROM Parking_Violations where `Issuer Precinct` = '14'
                   group by `Issuer Precinct`, `Violation Code`
                   order by tickets_count desc limit 5)

paragraphs.title: The Violation Time field is specified in a strange format. Find a way to make this into a time attribute that you can use to divide into groups.
paragraphs.text:
val tickets  =  Parking_Violations
                            .withColumn("Violation Timestamp",
                                    when (col("Violation Time").isNull,                                     lit(null).cast("timestamp")       /*$"Issue Date".cast("timestamp")*/   ).                      // Entries with null Violation Time
                                    when (col("Violation Time").substr(lit(-1),length($"Violation Time")) === 'A',  to_timestamp(concat($"Issue Date".cast("string"),lit(" "),$"Violation Time".substr(lit(1),length($"Violation Time")-1)),"yyyy-MM-dd hhmm" ) ).
                                    otherwise( to_timestamp(unix_timestamp(to_timestamp(concat($"Issue Date".cast("string"),lit(" "),$"Violation Time".substr(lit(1),length($"Violation Time")-1)),"yyyy-MM-dd hhmm" ))+43200 ))
                                    
            )
            .withColumn("Violation Timestamp Processed",$"Violation Timestamp".substr(lit(12),length($"Violation Timestamp")))

paragraphs.title: Divide 24 hours into six equal discrete bins of time. The intervals you choose are at your discretion. For each of these groups, find the three most commonly occurring violations.
paragraphs.text:
%sql

select `Violation Code`, count(*) tickets_count,

CASE 
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` is null THEN "UNKNOWN"
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` between "00:00:00" and "04:00:00" THEN "MIDNIGHT"
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` between "04:00:01" and "08:00:00" THEN "EARLY MORNING"
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` between "08:00:01" and "12:00:00" THEN "MORNING"
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` between "12:00:01" and "16:00:00" THEN "AFTERNOON"
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` between "16:00:01" and "20:00:00" THEN "EVENING"
    WHEN `Violation Timestamp Processed` between "20:00:01" and "23:59:99" THEN "LATE EVENING"
    
END AS TIME_SLOT


from tickets 

group by `Violation Code`,TIME_SLOT 

order by tickets_count desc 
limit 30

SELECT * FROM 
(
SELECT *, RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY SEASON ORDER BY tickets_count DESC) AS grouped_ronk
    FROM 
    (
        select `Violation Code`, count(*) tickets_count,

CASE 
    
    WHEN month(`Issue Date`) between 1 and 2 THEN "Winter"
    WHEN month(`Issue Date`) between 3 and 6 THEN "Summer"
    WHEN month(`Issue Date`) between 7 and 9 THEN "Rainy"
    WHEN month(`Issue Date`) between 9 and 12 THEN "Winter"
    
END AS SEASON

from tickets 

group by `Violation Code`,SEASON 
    )
)    
where grouped_ronk < 4

msg.data:
Then, visit the website:
http://www1.nyc.gov/site/finance/vehicles/services-violation-codes.page
It lists the fines associated with different violation codes. They’re divided into two categories, one for the highest-density locations of the city, the other for the rest of the city. For simplicity, take an average of the two.

21 – $55
36 – $50
38 – $50

paragraphs.text:
%sql

select 
`Violation Code`,count(1) count,
SUM(FINE) REVENUE
from 

(select *,
CASE 
    
    WHEN `Violation Code` = 21 THEN 55
    ELSE
        CASE WHEN `Violation Code` = 36 THEN 50 
        ELSE 
           CASE WHEN `Violation Code` = 38 THEN 50 
           ELSE 0
           END 
        END
   
    
END AS FINE
from tickets
)

group by `Violation Code`
order by REVENUE desc
limit 3
